author: @BigDudeSuperstar
text: "All Machine Learning is classification"   Only with discrete outcomes, right? I find this simplification way too coarse.    When you regress on continuous variables the outcome may (very well) be unbounded,  so the prediction may represent any value in Real valued space. Whereas classification is bounded in discrete and generally countable (Natural numbers) space.    Love your videos, but this is not exactly accurate.

author: @vegardwitsoe
text: Interesting video. However, I think that the part of installing python, scikit, numpy and mathplotlib is way too quickly glossed over and declared "very easy". For being a tutorial, it's not enough to just open a webpage and say "very easy". Some of these packages depends on Visual Studio, that's not mentioned. Visual Studio doesn't cooperate with Python at all, just out of the box. The version of Python that VS want's to cooperate with, is a totally different version than the one I alreaddy spent hours to download, install and debug with all addiotional packages. This went from "very easy" to "a headache taking most of my sunday, and still not working". I think, for a tutorial, picking the right versions of software and installing them correctly should be better covered.

text: The 64-bit version of Scikit-learn on the unofficial binaries list has gone missing! No worries, head to https://pypi.python.org/pypi/scikit-learn/0.15.2#downloads  There, you can find the 64-bit version of scikit-learn either as .exe or .whl. Being on pypi, you can also use pip with the .whl if you have a newer version of Python.
